## **How Commercial Organizations Staff Energy Management**

The staffing model for energy management varies sharply by organization size and type. This divide defines the market opportunity for Clear Current.

| **Org Type** | **Staffing Model** | **Energy Management Sophistication** | **Software Budget Authority** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Large public university | Dedicated energy manager + utilities team | High — CEM certified, district energy expertise | Director of Utilities; VP Facilities |
| Large hospital/health system | Facilities director + energy engineer | High — 24/7 critical load management | VP Facilities or CFO |
| Fortune 500 corporate | VP Sustainability or ESG team | Medium-High — ESG reporting-driven | Chief Sustainability Officer or CFO |
| Mid-market multi-site operator | Facilities manager (secondary responsibility) | Low-Medium — reactive, spreadsheet-based | VP Operations; CFO approval for >$15K |
| Small commercial (<10 locations) | Owner or office manager | Low — pays bills, no analysis | Owner-operator |

## **Key Staffing Statistics**

- Only 10% of organizations rely on a single person for energy management (EnergyCAP State of Utilities 2026)

- 64% of FM employers report difficulty finding technically skilled candidates (McMorrow Reports 2023)

- 66% of facility managers cite staffing and retention as their top challenge in 2023

- 76% of energy professionals expect utility budgets to increase YoY in 2026 (EnergyCAP)

- 69% say controlling/reducing utility spend is their #1 goal (EnergyCAP)

- 30%+ of facility and maintenance managers report difficulty finding skilled staff (Limble/Manufacturing.net 2021)

## **The Fake Energy Manager Persona**

| **KEY INSIGHT** | Primary interview research with Don Johnson (Trane Technologies) confirmed a critical buyer persona gap: many organizations carry someone with the 'Energy Manager' title who is functionally a facilities scheduler — not an energy analyst. This person has the title, is expected to perform analysis, but lacks the tools and expertise. Clear Current's emotional sell to this persona is professional credibility: 'a tool that quietly makes them competent.' |
