## **District Energy — The Complexity Driver**

District energy systems are the defining characteristic of university and hospital energy management. Understanding them is essential to understanding Clear Current's opportunity in higher education.

- Central plants produce steam and chilled water and distribute to hundreds of buildings via a buried pipe network

- Buildings don't receive vendor utility bills — the university becomes the 'local energy vendor' for its own departments

- Cost allocation requires percentage splits, formulas, and loss/remainder calculations that cannot be reduced to simple per-kWh billing

- Reimbursable facilities (athletics, dining, dorms, research) must pay market-rate internal bills requiring accurate metering

- Federal research grants require documented, auditable cost allocation — adding compliance complexity

- More than 20% of hospital buildings use district heating systems (PMC 2023)

- Hospitals consume ~9% of total U.S. commercial building energy while occupying only 4% of floorspace — 2.5x more energy per sq ft than office buildings

| **IMPLICATION** | EnergyCAP's campus chargeback capability is what keeps university customers in their platform despite UX frustrations. No AI-native competitor offers this capability. Building campus chargeback with a better-designed UX would create a defensible competitive moat. |
| --- | --- |

## **Typical University Energy Management Stack**

Based on EnergyCAP customer profiles and industry analysis:

- Utility bill management platform (EnergyCAP dominant) — ingests invoices, validates bills, allocates costs via chargeback

- Building Automation System (BAS) — multiple legacy systems coexist; 'a virtual museum of building automation systems' (University of Arizona energy manager)

- Interval data platform — at institutions with AMI deployment; enables load profile analysis

- ENERGY STAR Portfolio Manager — benchmarking against EPA standards

- Custom spreadsheets — still prevalent for specific chargeback calculations and custom reporting

